    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_364861924" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/364861924" />
    <a title="Ann" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10823104-ann"><img alt="Ann" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1507869723p2/10823104.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/364861924?book_show_action=true">Jul 09, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ann" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ann" href="/user/show/10823104-ann">Ann</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer364861924" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3325279576466560615">I&apos;ve long been a fan of Elizabeth George and her Inspector Lynley mystery series. I found this book to be somewhat of a disappointment, however, for a number of reasons. First, I have to say the flaws have nothing to do with the writing style. George is one of the best mystery writers out there today and her writing remains as strong as ever, even though the first Lynley book was published more than 20 years ago. <br/>My objections have more to do with the plot than anything else. Although I thought </span>
  <span id="freeText3325279576466560615" style="display:none">I've long been a fan of Elizabeth George and her Inspector Lynley mystery series. I found this book to be somewhat of a disappointment, however, for a number of reasons. First, I have to say the flaws have nothing to do with the writing style. George is one of the best mystery writers out there today and her writing remains as strong as ever, even though the first Lynley book was published more than 20 years ago. <br />My objections have more to do with the plot than anything else. Although I thought it was a nice touch for George to open the narrative with Inspector Lynley (Tommy) wandering forlornly along the English coast near Cornwall as an act of grief associated with the passing of his wife, this stands in too sharp a contrast with him then "falling for" another woman throughout subsequent pages. Perhaps this is unfair of me and a left-over bias for the much beloved Helen Lynley, who was murdered in the previous novel,but I just couldn't accept Tommy "moving on" so quickly. I give George credit for being subtle and not hitting the reader over the head with Tommy's burgeoning feelings of warmth toward Dairdre but well - it is what it is - too much too soon, especially in light of his solitary sojourn along the English coast. This journey, we are informed at novel's opening, lasts at least 43 days. <br />My second critique: At the risk of giving too much away, the revelation of Dairdre's past is somewhat anticlimatic, given the repeated instances in the book where it is revealed she has been caught in lies regarding key details in the murder investigation. I can only surmise George had a pang of conscience and panicked at the idea that our hero Tommy is -gasp - not only falling for another woman so quickly after Helen but he may actually be falling for a femme fatale. <br />My final critique: The ending is just awful. Again, too much of an anticlimax. Not only do we FINALLY find out who the murderer is but after he/she admits in so many words to doing the crime, the evidence can't be used because the confession is not really a confession but an allegorical revelation. It's just puzzling and frustrating. I suppose I must be spoiled by all those classic whodunnits where the murderer is caught, goes to trial and then jail and it's all wrapped up in a neat little package. Careless in Red is definitely not one of those types of mysteries. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3325279576466560615" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

