<div id="review_29947541" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/29947541" />
    <a title="Susanna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1418793-susanna"><img alt="Susanna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1335301512p2/1418793.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/29947541?book_show_action=true">Aug 12, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Susanna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Susanna" href="/user/show/1418793-susanna">Susanna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer29947541" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16548176481370856044">I was waiting in eager anticipation for this book for a long time, which I think was part of the problem. I definitely wouldn&apos;t recommend this to anyone who hasn&apos;t read some of the earlier books in the series, most importantly the last one, because this is a follow-up of the dramatic ending of that book. I thought it had about the right tone- it felt appropriate to the situation in which George had put her characters. But there was something about it that just didn&apos;t grab me. I didn&apos;t find the m</span>
  <span id="freeText16548176481370856044" style="display:none">I was waiting in eager anticipation for this book for a long time, which I think was part of the problem. I definitely wouldn't recommend this to anyone who hasn't read some of the earlier books in the series, most importantly the last one, because this is a follow-up of the dramatic ending of that book. I thought it had about the right tone- it felt appropriate to the situation in which George had put her characters. But there was something about it that just didn't grab me. I didn't find the mystery part compelling at all, which is unusual for me with George's books. What bothered me the most, though, was the total absence of Winston Nkata and, even more importantly, the minimal role played by Barbara Havers. The character of Havers has been what has kept me reading George's novels, even when she drones on about Deborah St. James, who mercifully did not appear in this book. I found the ending rather unsatisfying, but it was worth a read if only to discover how Lynley has dealt with his tragedy and to see the direction in which George seems to be taking her series.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16548176481370856044" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


