<div id="review_57050228" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/57050228" />
    <a title="Alarra" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/121123-alarra"><img alt="Alarra" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1184682450p2/121123.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/57050228?book_show_action=true">May 23, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alarra" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alarra" href="/user/show/121123-alarra">Alarra</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/121123-alarra?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer57050228" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13274600389861423382">In the aftermath of his wife&apos;s terrible death (which is the subject of the previous two books in the Lynley series), Thomas takes a walk along a deserted coastal path to try and escape everything in his life, but when he comes across a dead climber along a section of cliff, he is drawn back into police investigations, and into human contact once more. <br/><br/>I&apos;ve never believed in the character of Helen, and as callous as it sounds, I&apos;m kind of glad that she&apos;s dead, and giving greater complexity to the</span>
  <span id="freeText13274600389861423382" style="display:none">In the aftermath of his wife's terrible death (which is the subject of the previous two books in the Lynley series), Thomas takes a walk along a deserted coastal path to try and escape everything in his life, but when he comes across a dead climber along a section of cliff, he is drawn back into police investigations, and into human contact once more. <br /><br />I've never believed in the character of Helen, and as callous as it sounds, I'm kind of glad that she's dead, and giving greater complexity to the immaculate cipher that Lynley has always been. The murder mystery takes way too long to set up, since it involves an admittedly complex web of victims and suspects within a small Cornish town. Havers feels slightly forced into the narrative. There's a new female character who is a good foil to Lynley, but her arc becomes a redundant plot B that has a clumsy and altogether unsatisfactory resolution which annoyed me.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13274600389861423382" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


